<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="319" name="Plant Growth and Development">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Growth is regarded as one of the most fundamental and conspicuous characteristics of living beings. It is:</text>
            <option id="A">Irreversible permanent increase in size</option><option id="B">Reversible increase</option><option id="C">Temporary change</option><option id="D">Decreasing mass</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Definition of growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Growth in plants is largely restricted to specialized regions called:</text>
            <option id="A">Meristems</option><option id="B">Nodes</option><option id="C">Internodes</option><option id="D">Leaves</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Active cell division.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The form of growth wherein new cells are always being added to the plant body by the activity of meristem is called:</text>
            <option id="A">Open form of growth</option><option id="B">Closed form</option><option id="C">Determinate growth</option><option id="D">Secondary growth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Indeterminate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Increase in girth of dicot stems and roots is caused by:</text>
            <option id="A">Vascular cambium and Cork cambium</option><option id="B">Apical meristem</option><option id="C">Intercalary meristem</option><option id="D">Parenchyma</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Growth at cellular level is principally a consequence of increase in the amount of:</text>
            <option id="A">Protoplasm</option><option id="B">Cell wall</option><option id="C">Water</option><option id="D">Vacuole</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Living content.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The period of growth is generally divided into three phases: Meristematic, Elongation and:</text>
            <option id="A">Maturation</option><option id="B">Senescence</option><option id="C">Flowering</option><option id="D">Differentiation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Final phase.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cells proximal to the meristematic zone represent the phase of:</text>
            <option id="A">Elongation</option><option id="B">Maturation</option><option id="C">Division</option><option id="D">Differentiation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vacuolation occurs.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>S-shaped curve is typically obtained for:</text>
            <option id="A">Growth in natural environment (Sigmoid)</option><option id="B">Linear growth</option><option id="C">Arithmetic growth</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lag, log, stationary.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Development is a term that includes all changes that an organism goes through during its life cycle from:</text>
            <option id="A">Germination of seed to senescence</option><option id="B">Birth to death</option><option id="C">Flower to fruit</option><option id="D">Seed to seedling</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sum of growth and differentiation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Plasticity refers to:</text>
            <option id="A">Ability to follow different pathways in response to environment</option><option id="B">Rigidity</option><option id="C">Elasticity</option><option id="D">Growth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>E.g., Heterophylly.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Heterophylly is observed in:</text>
            <option id="A">Cotton, Coriander, Larkspur</option><option id="B">Maize</option><option id="C">Wheat</option><option id="D">Grass</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Different leaf shapes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Plant Growth Regulators (PGRs) are small, simple molecules of diverse chemical composition. Indole compounds include:</text>
            <option id="A">IAA (Auxin)</option><option id="B">Kinetin</option><option id="C">ABA</option><option id="D">GA3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Indole-3-acetic acid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Adenine derivatives include:</text>
            <option id="A">Kinetin (N6-furfurylamino purine)</option><option id="B">IAA</option><option id="C">GA3</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cytokinins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Carotenoids derivatives include:</text>
            <option id="A">Abscisic acid (ABA)</option><option id="B">IAA</option><option id="C">GA3</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stress hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Terpenes include:</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberellic acid (GA3)</option><option id="B">IAA</option><option id="C">Kinetin</option><option id="D">ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gibberellins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Discovery of Auxin is credited to:</text>
            <option id="A">Charles Darwin and Francis Darwin</option><option id="B">Sarl E. K.</option><option id="C">Skoog</option><option id="D">Cousins</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Canary grass experiment.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Auxin was first isolated from:</text>
            <option id="A">Human urine</option><option id="B">Corn germ oil</option><option id="C">Fungus</option><option id="D">Algae</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>By F.W. Went (isolated from tip actually, first isolated from urine refers to heteroauxin).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bakane (Foolish seedling) disease of rice is caused by:</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberella fujikuroi</option><option id="B">Virus</option><option id="C">Bacteria</option><option id="D">Insect</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fungal pathogen.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>E. Kurosawa (1926) reported the appearance of symptoms of Bakane disease by treating sterile filtrates of:</text>
            <option id="A">Fungus</option><option id="B">Bacteria</option><option id="C">Virus</option><option id="D">Algae</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Discovery of Gibberellins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>F. Skoog and co-workers observed that callus proliferation occurred only if medium was supplemented with:</text>
            <option id="A">Extracts of vascular tissues, yeast extract, coconut milk or DNA</option><option id="B">Only Auxin</option><option id="C">Sugar</option><option id="D">Water</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cytokinin discovery.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cousins confirmed the release of a volatile substance from ripened oranges that hastened ripening of bananas. This substance is:</text>
            <option id="A">Ethylene</option><option id="B">Abscisic acid</option><option id="C">Auxin</option><option id="D">Gibberellin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gaseous PGR.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Apical dominance is caused by:</text>
            <option id="A">Auxins</option><option id="B">Cytokinins</option><option id="C">Gibberellins</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Suppression of lateral buds.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bolting (internode elongation just prior to flowering) is promoted by:</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberellins</option><option id="B">Auxins</option><option id="C">Cytokinins</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Beet, Cabbage.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cytokinins help to overcome:</text>
            <option id="A">Apical dominance</option><option id="B">Dormancy</option><option id="C">Senescence</option><option id="D">Flowering</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Promote lateral growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which hormone is known as respiratory climacteric hormone?</text>
            <option id="A">Ethylene</option><option id="B">Auxin</option><option id="C">Ethephon</option><option id="D">ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases respiration rate.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Arithmetic growth is mathematically expressed as:</text>
            <option id="A">Lt = L0 + rt</option><option id="B">W1 = W0 e^rt</option><option id="C">L0 = Lt + rt</option><option id="D">Lt = rt</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Linear curve.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Geometric growth is mathematically expressed as:</text>
            <option id="A">W1 = W0 e^rt</option><option id="B">Lt = L0 + rt</option><option id="C">W1 = W0 + rt</option><option id="D">W0 = W1 e^rt</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exponential.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Absolute growth rate is:</text>
            <option id="A">Measurement and comparison of total growth per unit time</option><option id="B">Growth per unit initial parameter</option><option id="C">Total mass</option><option id="D">Height</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actual increase.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relative growth rate is:</text>
            <option id="A">Growth of the given system per unit time expressed on a common basis</option><option id="B">Total growth</option><option id="C">Absolute growth</option><option id="D">Height</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficiency index.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is essential for water turgidity of cells for extension growth?</text>
            <option id="A">Water</option><option id="B">Oxygen</option><option id="C">Nutrients</option><option id="D">Light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Turgor pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Differentiation is:</text>
            <option id="A">Cells derived from meristem mature to perform specific functions</option><option id="B">Cell division</option><option id="C">Death</option><option id="D">Growth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specialization.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dedifferentiation is:</text>
            <option id="A">Differentiated cells regain capacity to divide</option><option id="B">Loss of division</option><option id="C">Maturation</option><option id="D">Senescence</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of meristem.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Redifferentiation is:</text>
            <option id="A">Dedifferentiated cells again lose capacity to divide and mature</option><option id="B">Division</option><option id="C">Growth</option><option id="D">Death</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Second maturation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of dedifferentiation is:</text>
            <option id="A">Formation of cork cambium from parenchyma</option><option id="B">Formation of xylem</option><option id="C">Formation of phloem</option><option id="D">Root cap</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Interfascicular cambium too.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following generally act as growth promoters?</text>
            <option id="A">Auxins, Gibberellins, Cytokinins</option><option id="B">ABA, Ethylene</option><option id="C">Only Auxin</option><option id="D">Only ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Promote division/enlargement.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is a stress hormone?</text>
            <option id="A">Abscisic Acid (ABA)</option><option id="B">Ethylene</option><option id="C">Auxin</option><option id="D">GA3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tolerance to stress.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>IAA and IBA are:</text>
            <option id="A">Natural Auxins</option><option id="B">Synthetic Auxins</option><option id="C">Gibberellins</option><option id="D">Cytokinins</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Indole Acetic/Butyric Acid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>NAA and 2,4-D are:</text>
            <option id="A">Synthetic Auxins</option><option id="B">Natural Auxins</option><option id="C">Cytokinins</option><option id="D">Gibberellins</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Naphthalene acetic acid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Auxins are used to initiate rooting in:</text>
            <option id="A">Stem cuttings</option><option id="B">Leaves</option><option id="C">Flowers</option><option id="D">Roots</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Propagation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Auxins promote flowering in:</text>
            <option id="A">Pineapples</option><option id="B">Wheat</option><option id="C">Rice</option><option id="D">Maize</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific effect.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which auxin is used as a weedicide?</text>
            <option id="A">2,4-D</option><option id="B">IAA</option><option id="C">IBA</option><option id="D">NAA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kills dicot weeds.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Gibberellins cause fruits like apple to:</text>
            <option id="A">Elongate and improve shape</option><option id="B">Ripen</option><option id="C">Fall</option><option id="D">Rot</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fruit quality.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Spraying sugarcane crop with gibberellins increases yield by:</text>
            <option id="A">Increasing length of stem (up to 20 tonnes/acre)</option><option id="B">Increasing girth</option><option id="C">Increasing sugar content only</option><option id="D">Reducing disease</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Internode elongation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Natural cytokinins are synthesized in regions where:</text>
            <option id="A">Rapid cell division occurs (Root apices, developing shoot buds, young fruits)</option><option id="B">Leaves</option><option id="C">Old stems</option><option id="D">Bark</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Meristematic regions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cytokinins help to produce:</text>
            <option id="A">New leaves, chloroplasts in leaves</option><option id="B">Roots</option><option id="C">Stems</option><option id="D">Flowers only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Delay senescence.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which is the most widely used compound as source of ethylene?</text>
            <option id="A">Ethephon</option><option id="B">Ethane</option><option id="C">Auxin</option><option id="D">ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aqueous solution.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethylene promotes female flowers in:</text>
            <option id="A">Cucumbers</option><option id="B">Maize</option><option id="C">Wheat</option><option id="D">Rice</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases yield.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>ABA stimulates the closure of:</text>
            <option id="A">Stomata</option><option id="B">Lenticels</option><option id="C">Flowers</option><option id="D">Fruits</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water stress response.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>ABA acts as an antagonist to:</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberellins (GAs)</option><option id="B">Auxins</option><option id="C">Cytokinins</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Seed dormancy vs germination.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vernalization refers to promotion of flowering by:</text>
            <option id="A">Low temperature treatment</option><option id="B">High temperature</option><option id="C">Light</option><option id="D">Darkness</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cold treatment.</explanation>
        </question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Photoperiodism is the response of plants to:</text>
            <option id="A">Periods of day/night (Light duration)</option><option id="B">Light intensity</option><option id="C">Light quality</option><option id="D">Direction of light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Flowering trigger.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Long day plants flower when exposed to light duration:</text>
            <option id="A">Above a critical duration</option><option id="B">Below a critical duration</option><option id="C">Any duration</option><option id="D">No light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Need shorter nights.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Short day plants flower when exposed to light duration:</text>
            <option id="A">Below a critical duration</option><option id="B">Above a critical duration</option><option id="C">Any duration</option><option id="D">Continuous light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Need longer nights.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Day neutral plants show:</text>
            <option id="A">No correlation between exposure to light duration and flowering</option><option id="B">Response to temperature</option><option id="C">Response to blue light</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>E.g., Tomato.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The site of perception of light/dark duration is:</text>
            <option id="A">Leaves</option><option id="B">Stem tip</option><option id="C">Root</option><option id="D">Flower bud</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Florigen synthesis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vernalization prevents precocious reproductive development late in the growing season and enables plant to have sufficient time to reach:</text>
            <option id="A">Maturity</option><option id="B">Senescence</option><option id="C">Death</option><option id="D">Germination</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Qualitative/Quantitative requirement for cold.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following plants are biennial?</text>
            <option id="A">Sugarbeet, Cabbage, Carrot</option><option id="B">Wheat, Rice</option><option id="C">Mango, Neem</option><option id="D">Banyans</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Flowering in second year.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Seed dormancy is caused by:</text>
            <option id="A">Impermeable/hard seed coat, presence of chemical inhibitors (ABA, phenols)</option><option id="B">Immature embryo only</option><option id="C">Light</option><option id="D">Water</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Internal factors.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Seed dormancy can be broken by:</text>
            <option id="A">Mechanical abrasions (Scarification), Chilling treatment (Stratification), GA/Nitrates</option><option id="B">Heat only</option><option id="C">Drying</option><option id="D">Darkness</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Overcoming barriers.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Who crystallized Kinetin?</text>
            <option id="A">Skoog and Miller</option><option id="B">Darwin</option><option id="C">Went</option><option id="D">Kurosawa</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From herring sperm DNA.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which is natural: Zeatin or Kinetin?</text>
            <option id="A">Zeatin (from Corn kernels)</option><option id="B">Kinetin</option><option id="C">Both</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kinetin is synthetic/not natural in plants.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Parthenocarpy is induced by:</text>
            <option id="A">Auxins and Gibberellins</option><option id="B">ABA</option><option id="C">Cytokinin</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Seedless fruit (Tomatoes).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which PGR is used to induce flowering in mango?</text>
            <option id="A">Ethylene</option><option id="B">Auxin</option><option id="C">ABA</option><option id="D">GA3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Synchronizes flowering.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which PGR speeds up the malting process in brewing industry?</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberellin (GA3)</option><option id="B">Auxin</option><option id="C">Ethylene</option><option id="D">Cytokinin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Enzyme mobilization.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Early seed production in conifers is induced by:</text>
            <option id="A">Gibberellins (GAs)</option><option id="B">Auxins</option><option id="C">ABA</option><option id="D">Ethylene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hastens maturity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which PGR causes thinning of cotton, cherry and walnut?</text>
            <option id="A">Ethylene (Ethephon)</option><option id="B">Auxin</option><option id="C">GA3</option><option id="D">ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Abscission.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Nutrient mobilization making cells delay senescence is a function of:</text>
            <option id="A">Cytokinins</option><option id="B">Auxins</option><option id="C">GAs</option><option id="D">ABA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Richmond Lang effect.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which PGR prepares plants for winter?</text>
            <option id="A">ABA</option><option id="B">GA3</option><option id="C">Auxin</option><option id="D">Cytokinin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dormancy induction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Removal of shoot tip (Decapitation) results in:</text>
            <option id="A">Growth of lateral buds</option><option id="B">Death of plant</option><option id="C">Flowering</option><option id="D">Rooting</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tea plantations, Hedge making.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The parameter 'r' in growth equation is called:</text>
            <option id="A">Efficiency index</option><option id="B">Final size</option><option id="C">Time</option><option id="D">Initial size</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ability to produce new plant material.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Tracheary elements lose their protoplasm to:</text>
            <option id="A">Transport water efficiently</option><option id="B">Store food</option><option id="C">Divide</option><option id="D">Photosynthesize</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Differentiation example.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In arithmetic growth, the plot of length against time is:</text>
            <option id="A">Linear</option><option id="B">Sigmoid</option><option id="C">Parabolic</option><option id="D">Hyperbolic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constant rate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Exponential growth can be expressed as W1 = W0 e^rt. Here 'e' is:</text>
            <option id="A">Base of natural logarithms</option><option id="B">Energy</option><option id="C">Electron</option><option id="D">Efficiency</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mathematical constant.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is crucial for seed germination?</text>
            <option id="A">Water, Oxygen, Temperature</option><option id="B">Light only</option><option id="C">Soil only</option><option id="D">Nutrients only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>External factors.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethephon is absorbed by the plant and releases ethylene:</text>
            <option id="A">Slowly</option><option id="B">Rapidly</option><option id="C">Never</option><option id="D">Instantly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Controlled release.</explanation>
        </question>
    </hard>
</chapter>
